{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499451"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:00:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:00:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1508"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.21,0.08,0.43,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58305"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3464"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with an episode of abdominal pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. A clinical diagnosis of ureteric colic is made and this is confirmed by the identification on CT scanning of a 2 mm stone lodged in her right ureter. It is decided that the stone should be managed conservatively. However, the following is also found on CT scan (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the stomach","Hydatid cyst","Focal nodular hyperplasia","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Phytobezoar"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal stromal tumour (GIST)\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because of the well-circumscribed, homogenous mass in the stomach surrounded by oral contrast. These tumours usually occur after 40 years of age, and most commonly occur in the stomach. They are most likely to be asymptomatic, and are hence commonly discovered incidentally upon CT scan or endoscopy. Depending on their location in the digestive tract, GISTs are unlikely to cause symptoms until they are very large. If large, they can ulcerate and sometimes cause gastrointestinal haemorrhage. They also obstruct or may present with non-specific gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhytobezoars\u003C/strong\u003E are trapped masses within the gastrointestinal system consisting of indigestible plant matter. They are often associated with previous gastric surgery and typically are located in the small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are parasitic infections typically located within the liver, occurring due to ingesting food contaminated with E. granulosus eggs. The domestic dog is the main host of E. granulosus. They present on CT as well-defined encapsulated cystic or multicystic masses.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E may have no specific symptoms when they are superficial and potentially curable, although some patients have nonspecific gastrointestinal complaints such as dyspepsia. As it progresses they may present with anorexia, weight loss, as well as vague abdominal pain. If this lesion was a gastric cancer, it would almost certainly have produced symptoms by now.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal nodular hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a regenerative mass lesion located within the liver, and are usually asymptomatic. On non-contrast CT the lesions are usually hypo- or isoattenuating.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most gastrointestinal stromal tumours are now found incidentally (endoscopy or imaging)."],"references":["Akahoshi K, Oya M, Koga T et al. Current clinical management of gastrointestinal stromal tumor. World J Gastroenterol 2018; 24: 2806-17. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30018476/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58305"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1508"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15305"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15305"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f2bdaec6-2734-4bee-a765-3079288f1e80.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f2bdaec6-2734-4bee-a765-3079288f1e80.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":760,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58305"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:27:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T09:27:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1508"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72835"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tag